insensate.definition: Wanting sensibility; destitute of sense; stupid; foolish

insense.definition: To make to understand; to instruct

insensibility.definition: The state or quality of being insensible; lack of sensibility; torpor; unconsciousness; as, the insensibility produced by a fall, or by opiates
Lack of tenderness or susceptibility of emotion or passion; dullness; stupidity

insensible.definition: Destitute of the power of feeling or perceiving; wanting bodily sensibility; unconscious
Not susceptible of emotion or passion; void of feeling; apathetic; unconcerned; indifferent; as, insensible to danger, fear, love, etc.; -- often used with of or to
Incapable of being perceived by the senses; imperceptible. Hence: Progressing by imperceptible degrees; slow; gradual; as, insensible motion
Incapable of feeling a specific sensation or emotion; as, insensible to pity

insensibly.definition: In a manner not to be felt or perceived; imperceptibly; gradually

insensitive.definition: Not sensitive; wanting sensation, or wanting acute sensibility

insensuous.definition: Not sensuous; not pertaining to, affecting, or addressing, the senses

insentience.definition: The state or quality of being insentient; lacking consciousness or ability to perceive sensations

insentient.definition: Not sentient; not having perception, or the power of perception; devoid of feeling, consciousness and animation; inanimate; as, insentient stone.  Opposite of sentient

inseparability.definition: The quality or state of being inseparable; inseparableness

inseparable.definition: Not separable; incapable of being separated or disjoined
Invariably attached to some word, stem, or root; as, the inseparable particle un-

inseparableness.definition: The quality or state of being inseparable; inseparability

inseparably.definition: In an inseparable manner or condition; so as not to be separable

insert.definition: To set within something; to put or thrust in; to introduce; to cause to enter, or be included, or contained; as, to insert a scion in a stock; to insert a letter, word, or passage in a composition; to insert an advertisement in a newspaper

inserted.definition: Situated upon, attached to, or growing out of, some part; -- said especially of the parts of the flower; as, the calyx, corolla, and stamens of many flowers are inserted upon the receptacle

inserting.definition: Something inserted or set in, as lace, etc., in garments

insertion.definition: The act of inserting; as, the insertion of scions in stocks; the insertion of words or passages in writings
The condition or mode of being inserted or attached; as, the insertion of stamens in a calyx

That which is set in or inserted, such as a word or passage in a composition, or a narrow strip of embroidered lace, muslin, or cambric; as, there were numerous insertions and corrections to the first draft
The point or part by which a muscle or tendon is attached to the part to be moved; -- in contradistinction to its origin

inserve.definition: To be of use to an end; to serve

insession.definition: The act of sitting, as in a tub or bath
That in which one sits, as a bathing tub

insessor.definition: One of the Insessores. The group includes most of the common singing birds

insessores.definition: An order of birds, formerly established to include the perching birds, but now generally regarded as an artificial group

insessorial.definition: Pertaining to, or having the character of, perching birds
Belonging or pertaining to the Insessores

inset.definition: That which is inserted or set in; an insertion
One or more separate leaves inserted in a volume before binding

inseverable.definition: Incapable of being severed; indivisible; inseparable

inshave.definition: A plane for shaving or dressing the concave or inside faces of barrel staves

insheathe.definition: To insert as in a sheath; to sheathe

inshore.definition: Being near or moving towards the shore; as, inshore fisheries; inshore currents

insiccation.definition: The act or process of drying in

inside.definition: Within the sides of; in the interior; contained within; as, inside a house, book, bottle, etc
Being within; included or inclosed in anything; contained; interior; internal; as, the inside passengers of a stagecoach; inside decoration
The part within; interior or internal portion; content
The inward parts; entrails; bowels; hence, that which is within; private thoughts and feelings
An inside passenger of a coach or carriage, as distinguished from one upon the outside

insider.definition: an officer of a corporation or others who have access to private information about the corporation's operations, especially information relating to profitability

insidious.definition: Lying in wait; watching an opportunity to insnare or entrap; deceitful; sly; treacherous; -- said of persons; as, the insidious foe
Intended to entrap; characterized by treachery and deceit; as, insidious arts
Acting or proceeding unobserved or in a seemingly harmless manner, but slowly or eventually doing great damage; as, an insidious disease; an insidious plot

insidiousness.definition: A subtle and cumulative harmfulness, especially of a disease
the quality of being designed to entrap

insight.definition: A sight or view of the interior of anything; a deep inspection or view; introspection; -- frequently used with into
Power of acute observation and deduction; penetration; discernment; perception

insightful.definition: having intellectual depth; having or showing an exceptional degree of insight{2}; -- of people or their comments

insignia.definition: Distinguishing marks of authority, office, or honor; badges; tokens; decorations; as, the insignia of royalty or of an order
Typical and characteristic marks or signs, by which anything is known or distinguished; as, the insignia of a trade

insignificance.definition: The condition or quality of being insignificant; lack of significance, sense, or meaning; as, the insignificance of words or phrases
Lack of force or effect; unimportance; pettiness; inefficacy; as, the insignificance of human art
Lack of claim to consideration or notice; lack of influence or standing; meanness

insignificant.definition: Not significant; void of signification, sense, or import; meaningless; as, insignificant words
Having no weight or effect; answering no purpose; unimportant; valueless; futile
Without weight of character or social standing; mean; contemptible; as, an insignificant person

insignificantly.definition: without significance, importance, or effect; to no purpose

insincere.definition: Not being in truth what one appears to be; not sincere; dissembling; hypocritical; disingenuous; deceitful; false; -- said of persons; also of speech, thought; etc.; as, insincere declarations

insincerity.definition: The quality of being insincere; lack of sincerity, or of being in reality what one appears to be; dissimulation; hypocritical; deceitfulness; hollowness; untrustworthiness; as, the insincerity of a professed friend; the insincerity of professions of regard

insinew.definition: To strengthen, as with sinews; to invigorate

insinuate.definition: To introduce gently or slowly, as by a winding or narrow passage, or a gentle, persistent movement
To introduce artfully; to infuse gently; to instill
To hint; to suggest by remote allusion; -- often used derogatorily; as, did you mean to insinuate anything?
To push or work (one's self), as into favor; to introduce by slow, gentle, or artful means; to ingratiate; -- used reflexively
To creep, wind, or flow in; to enter gently, slowly, or imperceptibly, as into crevices
To ingratiate one's self; to obtain access or favor by flattery or cunning

insinuating.definition: Winding, creeping, or flowing in, quietly or stealthily; suggesting; winning favor and confidence insensibly

insinuation.definition: The act or process of insinuating; a creeping, winding, or flowing in
The act of gaining favor, affection, or influence, by gentle or artful means; -- formerly used in a good sense, as of friendly influence or interposition
The art or power of gaining good will by a prepossessing manner
That which is insinuated; a hint; a suggestion or intimation by distant allusion; as, slander may be conveyed by insinuations

insinuative.definition: Stealing on or into the confidence or affections; having power to gain favor
Using insinuations; giving hints; insinuating; as, insinuative remark

insinuator.definition: One who, or that which, insinuates

insipid.definition: Wanting in the qualities which affect the organs of taste; without taste or savor; vapid; tasteless; as, insipid drink or food
Wanting in spirit, life, or animation; uninteresting; weak; vapid; flat; dull; heavy; as, an insipid woman; an insipid composition

insipidity.definition: The quality or state of being insipid; vapidity

insipidly.definition: In an insipid manner; without taste, life, or spirit; flatly

insist.definition: To stand or rest; to find support; -- with in, on, or upon

To take a stand and refuse to give way; to hold to something firmly or determinedly; to be persistent, urgent, or pressing; to persist in demanding; -- followed by on, upon, or that; as, he insisted on these conditions; he insisted on going at once; he insists that he must have money

insistence.definition: The quality of insisting, or being urgent or pressing; the act of dwelling upon as of special importance; persistence; urgency

insistency.definition: the state of urgently demanding notice or attention; insistence
the quality of not being ignorable

insistent.definition: Standing or resting on something; as, an insistent wall

insisture.definition: A dwelling or standing on something; fixedness; persistence

insition.definition: The insertion of a scion in a stock; ingraftment

insnare.definition: To catch in a snare; to entrap; to take by artificial means
To take by wiles, stratagem, or deceit; to involve in difficulties or perplexities; to seduce by artifice; to inveigle; to allure; to entangle

insnarl.definition: To make into a snarl or knot; to entangle; to snarl

insobriety.definition: Lack of sobriety, moderation, or calmness; intemperance; drunkenness

insociability.definition: The quality of being insociable; lack of sociability; unsociability

insociable.definition: Incapable of being associated, joined, or connected
Not sociable or companionable; disinclined to social intercourse or conversation; unsociable; taciturn

insociate.definition: Not associate; without a companion; single; solitary; recluse

insolate.definition: To dry in, or to expose to, the sun's rays; to ripen or prepare by such exposure

insolation.definition: The act or process to exposing to the rays of the sun for the purpose of drying or maturing, as fruits, drugs, etc., or of rendering acid, as vinegar
The amount of sunlight impinging on the Earth's surface

insole.definition: The inside sole of a boot or shoe; also, a loose, thin strip of leather, felt, etc., placed inside the shoe for warmth or ease

insolence.definition: The quality of being unusual or novel
The quality of being insolent; pride or haughtiness manifested in contemptuous and overbearing treatment of others; arrogant contempt; brutal impudence

insolent.definition: Deviating from that which is customary; novel; strange; unusual
Haughty and contemptuous or brutal in behavior or language; overbearing; domineering; grossly rude or disrespectful; saucy; as, an insolent master; an insolent servant
Proceeding from or characterized by insolence; insulting; as, insolent words or behavior

insolidity.definition: Lack of solidity; weakness; as, the insolidity of an argument

insolubility.definition: The quality or state of being insoluble or not dissolvable, as in a fluid
The quality of being inexplicable or insolvable

insoluble.definition: Not soluble; in capable or difficult of being dissolved, as by a liquid; as, chalk is insoluble in water
Not to be solved or explained; insolvable; as, an insoluble doubt, question, or difficulty

insolubleness.definition: The quality or state of being insoluble; insolubility

insolvable.definition: Not solvable; insoluble; admitting no solution or explanation; as, an insolvable problem or difficulty
Incapable of being paid or discharged, as debts
Not capable of being loosed or disentangled; inextricable

insolvency.definition: The condition of being insolvent; the state or condition of a person who is insolvent; the condition of one who is unable to pay his debts as they fall due, or in the usual course of trade and business; as, a merchant's insolvency

insolvent.definition: Not solvent; not having sufficient estate to pay one's debts; unable to pay one's debts as they fall due, in the ordinary course of trade and business; as, in insolvent debtor
One who is insolvent; as insolvent debtor; -- in England, before 1861, especially applied to persons not traders

insomnia.definition: Lack of sleep; inability to sleep, especially when chronic; wakefulness; sleeplessness

insomuch.definition: So; to such a degree; in such wise; -- followed by that or as, and formerly sometimes by both.  Cf. Inasmuch

insoul.definition: To set a soul in; reflexively, to fix one's strongest affections on

inspan.definition: To yoke or harness, as oxen to a vehicle

inspect.definition: To look upon; to view closely and critically, esp. in order to ascertain quality or condition, to detect errors, etc., to examine; to scrutinize; to investigate; as, to inspect conduct
To view and examine officially, as troops, arms, goods offered, work done for the public, etc.; to oversee; to superintend

inspection.definition: The act or process of inspecting or looking at carefully; a strict or prying examination; close or careful scrutiny; investigation
The act of overseeing; official examination or superintendence

inspective.definition: Engaged in inspection; inspecting; involving inspection

inspector.definition: One who inspects, views, or oversees; one to whom the supervision of any work is committed; one who makes an official view or examination, as a military or civil officer; a superintendent; a supervisor; an overseer
A police officer, typically holding a rank one below superintendent, and in some cases in charge of several precincts; as, inspector Clousseau is investigating the case

inspectorial.definition: Of or pertaining to an inspector or to inspection

inspectorship.definition: The district embraced by an inspector's jurisdiction

inspeximus.definition: The first word of ancient charters in England, confirming a grant made by a former king; hence, a royal grant

insphere.definition: To place in, or as in, an orb a sphere.  Cf. Ensphere

inspirable.definition: Capable of being inspired or drawn into the lungs; inhalable; respirable; admitting inspiration

inspiration.definition: The act of inspiring or breathing in; breath; specif. (Physiol.), the drawing of air into the lungs, accomplished in mammals by elevation of the chest walls and flattening of the diaphragm; -- the opposite of expiration

The act or power of exercising an elevating or stimulating influence upon the intellect or emotions; the result of such influence which quickens or stimulates; as, the inspiration of occasion, of art, etc

A supernatural divine influence on the prophets, apostles, or sacred writers, by which they were qualified to communicate moral or religious truth with authority; a supernatural influence which qualifies men to receive and communicate divine truth; also, the truth communicated

inspirational.definition: Imparting inspiration{2}; as, an inspirational sermon

inspirator.definition: A kind of injector for forcing water by steam. See Injector, n., 2

inspiratory.definition: Pertaining to, or aiding, inspiration; as, the inspiratory muscles

inspire.definition: To breathe into; to fill with the breath; to animate
To infuse by breathing, or as if by breathing
To draw in by the operation of breathing; to inhale; -- opposed to expire
To infuse into the mind; to communicate to the spirit; to convey, as by a divine or supernatural influence; to disclose preternaturally; to produce in, as by inspiration

To infuse into; to affect, as with a superior or supernatural influence; to fill with what animates, enlivens, or exalts; to communicate inspiration to; as, to inspire a child with sentiments of virtue; to inspire a person to do extraordinary feats
To draw in breath; to inhale air into the lungs; -- opposed to expire

inspired.definition: Moved or animated by, or as by, a supernatural influence; affected by divine inspiration; as, the inspired prophets; the inspired writers

Communicated or given as by supernatural or divine inspiration; having divine authority; hence, sacred, holy; -- opposed to uninspired, profane, or secular; as, the inspired writings, that is, the Scriptures
Moved to a higher level of thought, creativity, or motivation

inspirer.definition: One who, or that which, inspires

inspiring.definition: Animating; cheering; moving; exhilarating; as, an inspiring or scene

inspirit.definition: To infuse new life or spirit into; to animate; to encourage; to invigorate

inspissate.definition: To thicken or bring to greater consistence, as fluids by evaporation

inspissation.definition: The act or the process of inspissating, or thickening a fluid substance, as by evaporation; also, the state of being so thickened

inst..definition: in or of the present month; same as instant{3}, a. or instant{2}, n.; as, your letter of the 10th inst

instability.definition: The quality or condition of being unstable; lack of stability, firmness, or steadiness; liability to give way or to fail; insecurity; precariousness; as, the instability of a building
Lack of determination of fixedness; inconstancy; fickleness; mutability; changeableness; as, instability of character, temper, custom, etc

instable.definition: Not stable; not standing fast or firm; unstable; prone to change or recede from a purpose; mutable; inconstant

install.definition: To set in a seat; to give a place to; establish (one) in a place

To place in an office, rank, or order; to invest with any charge by the usual ceremonies; to instate; to induct; as, to install an ordained minister as pastor of a church; to install a college president

installation.definition: The act of installing; as, the installation of the air conditioner took half an hour
the act of installing (a person) or giving possession of an office, rank, or order, with the usual rites or ceremonies; as, the installation of an ordained minister in a parish

The whole of a system of machines, apparatus, and accessories, sometimes including the buildings and gorounds on which they are located, when set up and arranged for practical working, as in electric lighting, transmission of power, etc.; as, our installation in Baton Rouge can produce ten thousand gallons a day;  we should move our drying installation from building A to building B
The whole of a military base, post, camp, outpost, etc., constructed and operated for support of military operations

installing.definition: the act of installing something (as equipment)

installment.definition: The seat in which one is placed

A portion of a debt, or sum of money, which is divided into portions that are made payable at different times; that portion of a debt payed back in any one payment; as, the next installment is due January first.  Payment by installment is payment by parts at different times, the amounts and times being often definitely stipulated
a part of a broadcast serial
a part of a published serial

instance.definition: The act or quality of being instant or pressing; urgency; solicitation; application; suggestion; motion
That which is instant or urgent; motive

That which offers itself or is offered as an illustrative case; something cited in proof or exemplification; a case occurring; an example; as, we could find no instance of poisoning in the town within the past year
A token; a sign; a symptom or indication
To mention as a case or example; to refer to; to cite; as, to instance a fact

instant.definition: Closely pressing or impending in respect to time; not deferred; immediate; without delay
A point in time; a moment; a portion of time too short to be estimated; also, any particular moment; as, the situation may change in an instant
A day of the present or current month; as, the sixth instant; -- an elliptical expression equivalent to the sixth of the month instant, i. e., the current month. See Instant, a., 3

instantaneous.definition: Done or occurring in an instant, or without any perceptible duration of time; as, the passage of electricity appears to be instantaneous
At or during a given instant; as, instantaneous acceleration, velocity, etc

instanter.definition: Immediately; instantly; at once; as, he left instanter

instantly.definition: Without the least delay or interval; at once; immediately
With urgency or importunity; earnestly; pressingly

instar.definition: a postembryonic stage of life of an arthropod, especially an insect, between two successive molts; also, the arthropod when in that stage of life

instate.definition: To set, place, or establish, as in a rank, office, or condition; to install; to invest; as, to instate a person in greatness or in favor

instauration.definition: Restoration after decay, lapse, or dilapidation; renewal; repair; renovation; renaissance

instaurator.definition: One who renews or restores to a former condition

instaure.definition: To renew or renovate; to instaurate

instead.definition: In the place or room; -- usually followed by of
Equivalent; equal to; -- usually with of

insteep.definition: To steep or soak; to drench

instep.definition: The arched middle portion of the human foot next in front of the ankle joint
The part of a shoe, boot, or stocking covering the instep{1}
That part of the hind leg of the horse and allied animals, between the hock, or ham, and the pastern joint

instigant.definition: one who instigates; someone who deliberately provokes trouble; an instigator

instigate.definition: To goad or urge forward; to set on; to provoke; to incite; -- used chiefly with reference to evil actions; as, to instigate one to a crime

instigation.definition: The act of instigating, or the state of being instigated; incitement; esp. to evil or wickedness

synonyms: Syn. -- incendiary, incitive, inflammatory, rabble-rousing, seditious.

instill.definition: To drop in; to pour in drop by drop
To infuse (knowledge or attitudes) into the mind of another, slowly or gradually; to impart gradually; to cause to be imbibed

instillation.definition: The act of instilling; also, that which is instilled

instillment.definition: The act of instilling; also, that which is instilled

instimulate.definition: Not to stimulate; to soothe; to quiet

instinct.definition: Urged or stimulated from within; naturally moved or impelled; imbued; animated; alive; quick; as, birds instinct with life
Natural inward impulse; unconscious, involuntary, or unreasoning prompting to any mode of action, whether bodily, or mental, without a distinct apprehension of the end or object to be accomplished
Specif., the natural, unreasoning, impulse by which an animal is guided to the performance of any action, without thought of improvement in the method
A natural aptitude or knack; a predilection; as, an instinct for order; to be modest by instinct
To impress, as an animating power, or instinct

instinctive.definition: Of or pertaining to instinct; derived from, or prompted by, instinct; of the nature of instinct; determined by natural impulse or propensity; acting or produced without reasoning, deliberation, instruction, or experience; spontaneous

instinctively.definition: In an instinctive manner; by force of instinct; by natural impulse

instinctivity.definition: The quality of being instinctive, or prompted by instinct

institute.definition: To set up; to establish; to ordain; as, to institute laws, rules, etc
To originate and establish; to found; to organize; as, to institute a court, or a society
To begin; to commence; to set on foot; as, to institute an inquiry; to institute a suit
To ground or establish in principles and rudiments; to educate; to instruct
To invest with the spiritual charge of a benefice, or the care of souls
That which is instituted, established, or fixed, as a law, habit, or custom

Hence: An elementary and necessary principle; a precept, maxim, or rule, recognized as established and authoritative; usually in the plural, a collection of such principles and precepts; esp., a comprehensive summary of legal principles and decisions; as, the Institutes of Justinian; Coke's Institutes of the Laws of England.  Cf. Digest, n

An institution; a society established for the promotion of learning, art, science, etc.; a college; as, the Institute of Technology; The Massachusetts Institute of Technology; also, a building owned or occupied by such an institute; as, the Cooper Institute
The person to whom an estate is first given by destination or limitation

institution.definition: The act or process of instituting; as: (a) Establishment; foundation; enactment; as, the institution of a school

An established or organized society or corporation; an establishment, especially of a public character, or affecting a community; a foundation; as, a literary institution; a charitable institution; also, a building or the buildings occupied or used by such organization; as, the Smithsonian Institution
That which institutes or instructs; a textbook; a system of elements or rules; an institute

institutional.definition: Pertaining to, or treating of, an institution or institutions; as, institutional legends

institutionary.definition: Relating to an institution, or institutions
Containing the first principles or doctrines; elemental; rudimentary

institutist.definition: A writer or compiler of, or a commentator on, institutes

institutive.definition: Tending or intended to institute; having the power to establish
Established; depending on, or characterized by, institution or order

institutor.definition: One who institutes, founds, ordains, or establishes
A presbyter appointed by the bishop to institute a rector or assistant minister over a parish church

instop.definition: To stop; to close; to make fast; as, to instop the seams

instore.definition: To store up; to inclose; to contain

instroke.definition: An inward stroke; specif., in a steam or other engine, a stroke in which the piston is moving away from the crank shaft; -- opposed to outstroke

instruct.definition: To put in order; to form; to prepare
To form by communication of knowledge; to inform the mind of; to impart knowledge or information to; to enlighten; to teach; to discipline
To furnish with directions; to advise; to direct; to command; as, the judge instructs the jury

instructible.definition: Capable of being instructed; teachable; docible

instruction.definition: The act of instructing, teaching, or furnishing with knowledge; information
That which instructs, or with which one is instructed; the intelligence or information imparted

a segment of coded data that is interpreted by a computer as a command to perform an operation or series of operations.  The term instruction is applied to both the electronic form of the data as represented in and executed by the computer, and to any line of written computer code which is interpreted as one instruction by a compiler.  A computer program is comprised of one or more instructions
synonyms: Syn. -- command, statement, line of code, program line.

instructional.definition: Pertaining to, or promoting, instruction; educational

instructive.definition: Conveying knowledge; serving to instruct or inform; as, experience furnishes very instructive lessons

instructor.definition: One who instructs; one who imparts knowledge to another; a teacher

instructorship.definition: the office or position of an instructor

instructress.definition: A woman who instructs; a preceptress; a governess

instrument.definition: That by means of which any work is performed, or result is effected; a tool; a utensil; an implement; a device; as, the instruments of a mechanic; astronomical instruments
A contrivance or implement, by which musical sounds are produced; as, a musical instrument
A writing, as the means of giving formal expression to some act; a writing expressive of some act, contract, process, as a deed, contract, writ, etc
One who, or that which, is made a means, or is caused to serve a purpose; a medium, means, or agent; as, their army was primarily an instrument of oppression
To perform upon an instrument; to prepare for an instrument; as, a sonata instrumented for orchestra
To furnish or equip with instruments; to attach instruments to; as, the fighter planes were heavily instrumented; the patient was instrumented to monitor him remotely

instrumental.definition: Acting as an instrument; serving as a means; contributing to promote; conductive; helpful; serviceable; as, he was instrumental in conducting the business
Pertaining to, made by, or prepared for, an instrument, esp. a musical instrument; as, instrumental music, distinguished from vocal music

Applied to a case expressing means or agency; as, the instrumental case. This is found in Sanskrit and Russian as a separate case, but in Greek it was merged into the dative, and in Latin into the ablative. In Old English it was a separate case, but has disappeared, leaving only a few anomalous forms

instrumentalism.definition: The view that the sanction of truth is its utility, or that truth is genuine only in so far as it is a valuable instrument

instrumentalist.definition: One who plays upon an instrument of music, as distinguished from a vocalist

instrumentality.definition: The quality or condition of being instrumental; that which is instrumental; anything used as a means; medium; agency

instrumentally.definition: By means of an instrument or agency; as means to an end
With instruments of music; as, a song instrumentally accompanied

instrumentalness.definition: Usefulness or agency, as means to an end; instrumentality

instrumentation.definition: The act of using or adapting as an instrument; a series or combination of instruments; means; agency
The arrangement of a musical composition for performance by a number of different instruments; orchestration; instrumental composition; composition for an orchestra or military band
The act of using instruments to measure or control the behavior of an object, as a patient in a hospital or a machine being tested while under development
The act of furnishing or attaching instruments to/
The set of instruments included in a system; as, a harvester with modern instrumentation

instrumented.definition: Having instruments attached for the purpose of measuring conditions while under observation; -- said of a person under medical observation or a machine whose performance is being tested

instrumentist.definition: A performer on a musical instrument; an instrumentalist

insubjection.definition: Lack of subjection or obedience; a state of disobedience, as to government

insubmergible.definition: Not capable of being submerged; buoyant

insubordinate.definition: Not submitting to authority; disobedient; rebellious; mutinous

insubordination.definition: The quality of being insubordinate; disobedience to lawful authority

insuccation.definition: The act of soaking or moistening; maceration; solution in the juice of herbs

insuetude.definition: The state or quality of being unaccustomed; absence of use or habit

insufferable.definition: Incapable of being suffered, borne, or endured; insupportable; unendurable; intolerable; as, insufferable heat, cold, or pain; insufferable wrongs

insufferably.definition: In a manner or to a degree beyond endurance; intolerably; as, a blaze insufferably bright; a person insufferably proud

insufficiency.definition: The quality or state of being insufficient; lack of sufficiency; deficiency; inadequateness; as, the insufficiency of provisions, of an excuse, etc
Lack of power or skill; inability; incapacity; incompetency; as, the insufficiency of a man for an office

insufficient.definition: Not sufficient; not enough; inadequate to any need, use, or purpose; as, the provisions are insufficient in quantity, and defective in quality
Wanting in strength, power, ability, capacity, or skill; incompetent; incapable; unfit; as, a person insufficient to discharge the duties of an office

insufficiently.definition: In an insufficient manner or degree; unadequately

insufflate.definition: To blow upon; to breath upon or into; to use insufflation upon

insufflation.definition: The act of breathing on or into anything

insular.definition: Of or pertaining to an island; of the nature, or possessing the characteristics, of an island; as, an insular climate, fauna, etc
Of or pertaining to the people of an island; narrow; circumscribed; illiberal; contracted; as, insular habits, opinions, or prejudices

insularity.definition: The state or quality of being an island or consisting of islands; insulation
Narrowness or illiberality of opinion; prejudice; exclusiveness; as, the insularity of the Chinese or of the aristocracy

insulate.definition: To place in a detached situation, or in a state having no communication with surrounding objects; to isolate; to separate
To prevent the transfer of electricity or heat to or from (bodies) by the interposition of nonconductors

insulated.definition: Standing by itself; not being contiguous to other bodies; separated; unconnected; isolated; as, an insulated house or column
Separated from other bodies by means of nonconductors of heat or electricity
Situated at so great a distance as to be beyond the effect of gravitation; -- said of stars supposed to be so far apart that the affect of their mutual attraction is insensible

insulation.definition: The act of insulating, or the state of being insulated; detachment from other objects; isolation

insulator.definition: One who, or that which, insulates

insult.definition: The act of leaping on; onset; attack

To leap or trample upon; to make a sudden onset upon
To treat with abuse, insolence, indignity, or contempt, by word or action; to abuse; as, to call a man a coward or a liar, or to sneer at him, is to insult him
To behave with insolence; to exult

insultable.definition: Capable of being insulted or affronted

insultation.definition: The act of insulting; abusive or insolent treatment; insult

insulting.definition: Containing, or characterized by, insult or abuse; tending to insult or affront; as, insulting language, treatment, etc

insuperability.definition: The quality or state of being insuperable; insuperableness

insupportable.definition: Incapable of being supported or borne; unendurable; insufferable; intolerable; as, insupportable burdens; insupportable pain

insuppressible.definition: That can not be suppressed or concealed; irrepressible

The sum for which life or property is insured
A guaranty, security, or pledge; assurance
Any means of assuring against loss; a precaution; as, we always use our seat belts as insurance against injury

insurancer.definition: One who effects insurance; an insurer; an underwriter

insurant.definition: The person insured, called also the insured

To underwrite; to make insurance; as, a company insures at three per cent

insurer.definition: One who, or that which, insures; the person or company that contracts to indemnify losses for a premium; an underwriter

insurgence.definition: A state of insurrection; an uprising; an insurrection

insurmountability.definition: The state or quality of being insurmountable

insurmountableness.definition: The state or quality of being insurmountable; insurmountability

insurmountably.definition: In a manner or to a degree not to be overcome

insurrection.definition: A rising against civil or political authority, or the established government; open and active opposition to the execution of law in a city or state

insusurration.definition: The act of whispering into something

inswathe.definition: To wrap up; to infold; to swathe

having constituent parts mixed to form a single unit.  Opposite of unmixed

Unimpaired, unadulterated, or genuine state; entire correspondence with an original condition; purity

Capable of being perceived by the understanding only, not by the senses

Relating to the understanding; treating of the mind; as, intellectual philosophy, sometimes called “mental” philosophy
The intellect or understanding; mental powers or faculties
A learned person or one of high intelligence

Preference for activities involving exercise of the intellect

One who accepts the doctrine of intellectualism

intellectuality.definition: Intellectual powers; possession of intellect; quality of being intellectual

To endow with intellect; to bestow intellectual qualities upon; to cause to become intellectual

intelligence.definition: The act or state of knowing; the exercise of the understanding

intelligencer.definition: One who, or that which, sends or conveys intelligence or news; a messenger

intelligent.definition: Endowed with the faculty of understanding or reason; as, man is an intelligent being

intelligentsia.definition: an educated and intellectual{2} elite; intellectuals, collectively or considered as a class

That which intensifies or emphasizes; an intensive verb or word

intensiveness.definition: The quality or state of being intensive; intensity

interface.definition: a surface forming a common boundary between two things, especially between two fluids
hardware that links one device with another (especially a computer)

That part of a computer program which controls the way a program interacts with a user; the manner of inputting and outputting of data, and the way information is presented on a computer monitor; also called user interface; as, a graphical user interface; a character-based interface

interfacial.definition: Included between two plane surfaces or faces; as, an interfacial angle
Of or pertaining to an interface

interfaith.definition: involving persons of different religious faiths; as, an interfaith marriage; interfaith good will

interfascicular.definition: Between fascicles or bundles; as, the interfascicular spaces of connective tissue

interferant.definition: One of the contestants in interference before the Patent Office

interfere.definition: To come in collision; to be in opposition; to clash; -- usually used with with; as, interfering claims, or commands; workers in a crowded shop may interfere with each other's activity
To enter into, or take a part in, the concerns of others; to intermeddle; to interpose; -- used with in or with; as, to interfere with the way I raise my children
To strike one foot against the opposite foot or ankle in using the legs; -- sometimes said of a human being, but usually of a horse; as, the horse interferes
To act reciprocally, so as to augment, diminish, or otherwise affect one another; -- said of waves, rays of light, heat, etc. See Interference, 2
To cover the same ground; to claim the same invention; as, to interfere with another patent

interference.definition: The act or state of interfering; as, the stoppage of a machine by the interference of some of its parts; a meddlesome interference in the business of others

The mutual influence, under certain conditions, as from streams of light, or pulsations of sound, or, generally, two waves or vibrations of any kind, producing certain characteristic phenomena, as colored fringes, dark bands, or darkness, in the case of light, silence or increased intensity in sounds; neutralization or superposition of waves generally
The act or state of interfering, or of claiming a right to the same invention

interferometer.definition: An instrument for measuring small movements, distances, or displacements by means of the interference of two beams of light; -- formerly also called also refractometer, but that word now has a different meaning

interfoliaceous.definition: At the same node with opposite or whorled leaves, but occupying a position between their places of attachment

interfollicular.definition: Between follicles; as, the interfollicular septa in a lymphatic gland

interfretted.definition: Interlaced; linked together; -- said of charges or bearings. See Fretted

interfuse.definition: To pour or spread between or among; to diffuse; to scatter
To spread through; to permeate; to pervade
To mix up together; to associate

interfusion.definition: The act of interfusing, or the state of being interfused

interganglionic.definition: Between and uniting the nervous ganglions; as, interganglionic cords

interglobular.definition: Between globules; -- applied esp. to certain small spaces, surrounded by minute globules, in dentine

intergrave.definition: To grave or carve between; to engrave in the alternate sections

interhemal.definition: Between the hemal arches or hemal spines

interhyal.definition: Of or pertaining to a segment sometimes present at the proximal end of the hyoidean arch

interim.definition: The meantime; time intervening; interval between events, etc
A name given to each of three compromises made by the emperor Charles V. of Germany for the sake of harmonizing the connecting opinions of Protestants and Catholics

interior.definition: Being within any limits, inclosure, or substance; inside; internal; inner; -- opposed to exterior, or superficial; as, the interior apartments of a house; the interior surface of a hollow ball
Remote from the limits, frontier, or shore; inland; as, the interior parts of a region or country
That which is within; the internal or inner part of a thing; the inside
The inland part of a country, state, or kingdom

interiorise.definition: to incorporate within oneself; same as interiorize

interjacence.definition: The state of being between; a coming or lying between or among; intervention; also, that which lies between

interjacent.definition: Lying or being between or among; intervening; as, interjacent isles

interjangle.definition: To make a dissonant, discordant noise one with another; to talk or chatter noisily

interject.definition: To throw in between; to insert; to interpose
To throw one's self between or among; to come between; to interpose

interjection.definition: The act of interjecting or throwing between; also, that which is interjected
A word or form of speech thrown in to express emotion or feeling, as O! Alas! Ha ha! Begone! etc. Compare Exclamation

interjectional.definition: Thrown in between other words or phrases; parenthetical; ejaculatory; as, an interjectional remark
Pertaining to, or having the nature of, an interjection; consisting of natural and spontaneous exclamations

interjectionalize.definition: To convert into, or to use as, an interjection

interjoist.definition: The space or interval between two joists

interknit.definition: To knit together; to unite closely; to intertwine

interlace.definition: To unite, as by lacing together; to insert or interpose one thing within another; to intertwine; to interweave

interlacement.definition: The act of interlacing, or the state of being interlaced; also, that which is interlaced

interlamellar.definition: Between lammellæ or laminæ; as, interlamellar spaces

interlaminated.definition: Placed between, or containing, laminæ or plates

interlapse.definition: The lapse or interval of time between two events

interlard.definition: To place lard or bacon amongst; to mix, as fat meat with lean
Hence: To insert between; to mix or mingle; especially, to introduce that which is foreign or irrelevant; as, to interlard a conversation with oaths or allusions

interlay.definition: To lay or place among or between

interleaf.definition: A leaf inserted between other leaves; a blank leaf inserted, as in a book

interleave.definition: To insert a leaf or leaves in; to bind with blank leaves inserted between the others; as, to interleave a book
To insert something alternately between the parts of; as, to interleave transparencies with the corresponding pages

interline.definition: To write or insert between lines already written or printed, as for correction or addition; to write or print something between the lines of; as, to interline a page or a book
To arrange in alternate lines; as, to interline Latin and English
To mark or imprint with lines

interlineal.definition: Contained between lines; written or inserted between lines already written or printed; containing interlineations; as, an interlinear manuscript, translation, etc

interlineation.definition: That which is interlined; a passage, word, or line inserted between lines already written or printed

interlingua.definition: A language used as an intermediate language in translating from a source language to a target language; -- used especially in machine translation by computers; as, some machine translation systems use Esperanto as an interlingua

interlining.definition: Correction or alteration by writing between the lines; interlineation

interlink.definition: To link together; to join, as one chain to another

interlobar.definition: Between lobes; as, the interlobar notch of the liver; the interlobar ducts of a gland

interlobular.definition: Between lobules; as, the interlobular branches of the portal vein

interlocation.definition: A placing or coming between; interposition

interlock.definition: To unite, embrace, communicate with, or flow into, one another; to be connected in one system; to lock into one another; to interlace firmly
To unite by locking or linking together; to secure in place by mutual fastening
To connect together so that the parts work together as a coordinated unit; to connect as a single system

interlocking.definition: Connected together in such a manner that the parts work together as a single unit, or in a coordianted manner

interlocution.definition: Interchange of speech; dialogue; conversation; conference
An intermediate act or decree before final decision

interlocutor.definition: One who takes part in dialogue or conversation; a talker, interpreter, or questioner

interlocutory.definition: Consisting of, or having the nature of, dialogue; conversational
Intermediate; not final or definitive; made or done during the progress of an action; as, an interlocutory judgement

interlope.definition: To run between parties and intercept without right the advantage that one should gain from the other; to traffic without a proper license; to intrude; to forestall others; to intermeddle

interloper.definition: One who interlopes; one who unlawfully intrudes upon a property, a station, or an office; one who interferes wrongfully or officiously

interlucate.definition: To let in light upon, as by cutting away branches

interlucation.definition: Act of thinning a wood to let in light

interlude.definition: A short entertainment exhibited on the stage between the acts of a play, or between the play and the afterpiece, to relieve the tedium of waiting
A form of English drama or play, usually short, merry, and farcical, which succeeded the Moralities or Moral Plays in the transition to the romantic or Elizabethan drama

A short piece of instrumental music played between the parts of a song or cantata, or the acts of a drama; especially, in church music, a short passage played by the organist between the stanzas of a hymn, or in German chorals after each line
Any intervening period of time, space, etc.; a pause between phases of an activity

interluded.definition: Inserted in the manner of an interlude; having or containing interludes

interluder.definition: An actor who performs in an interlude

interlunar.definition: Belonging or pertaining to the time when the moon, at or near its conjunction with the sun, is invisible

intermandibular.definition: Between the mandibles; interramal; as, the intermandibular space

intermarriage.definition: Connection by marriage; reciprocal marriage; giving and taking in marriage, as between two families, tribes, races, castes, or nations

intermarry.definition: To become connected by marriage between their members; to give and take mutually in marriage; -- said of families, ranks, races, castes, etc

intermean.definition: Something done in the meantime; interlude

intermeddle.definition: To meddle with the affairs of others; to meddle officiously; to interpose or interfere improperly; to mix or meddle with

intermeddler.definition: One who meddles with, or intrudes into, the affairs of others

intermede.definition: A short musical dramatic piece, of a light and pleasing, sometimes a burlesque, character; an interlude introduced between the acts of a play or an opera

intermediae.definition: The middle pair of tail feathers, or middle rectrices

intermediary.definition: Lying, coming, or done, between; intermediate; as, an intermediary project
One who, or that which, is intermediate; an interagent; a go-between; a mediator

intermediate.definition: Lying or being in the middle place or degree, or between two extremes; coming or done between; intervening; interposed; interjacent; as, an intermediate space or time; intermediate colors
Of or pertaining to an intermediate school; as, intermediate education
To come between; to intervene; to interpose
A person who intermediates between others, especially in negotiations; an intermediary; a mediator

A compound which is produced in the course of a chemical synthesis, which is not itself the final product, but is used in further reactions which produce the final product; also called synthetic intermediate, intermediate compound or intermediate product; -- contrasted to starting material and end product or final product.  There may be many different intermediates between the starting material and end product in the course of a complex synthesis; as, many industrial chemicals are produced primarily to be used as intermediates in other syntheses

intermediate school.definition: A school having grades at a level between the lower primary grades and the upper secondary grades, being variously grades 4 through 6, or grades 7 through 9, etc

intermediately.definition: In an intermediate manner; by way of intervention

intermediation.definition: The act of coming between; intervention; mediation; interposition

intermedium.definition: The bone or cartilage between the radiale and ulnare in the carpus, and between the tibiale and fibulare in the tarsus. It corresponds to the lunar in the carpus, and to a part of the astragalus in the tarsus of man and most mammals

intermembral.definition: Between members or limbs; as, intermembral homology, the correspondence of the limbs with each other

intermembranous.definition: Within or beneath a membrane; as, intermembranous ossification

interment.definition: The act or ceremony of depositing a dead body in the earth; burial; sepulture; inhumation

intermention.definition: To mention among other things, or casually or incidentally

intermesenteric.definition: Within the mesentery; as, the intermesenteric, or aortic, plexus

intermezzo.definition: An interlude; an intermede. See Intermede

intermicate.definition: To flash or shine between or among

intermigration.definition: Reciprocal migration; interchange of dwelling place by migration

interminable.definition: Without termination; admitting no limit; boundless; endless; wearisomely protracted; as, interminable space or duration; interminable sufferings; an interminable sermon

intermine.definition: To intersect or penetrate with mines

intermingle.definition: To mingle or mix together; to intermix

intermission.definition: The act or the state of intermitting; the state of being neglected or disused; disuse; discontinuance
Cessation for a time; an intervening period of time; an interval; a temporary pause; as, to labor without intermission; an intermission of ten minutes
The short period between acts of a play, concert, opera, or other public performance when the audience may leave their seats for refreshment; -- it usually lasts from 10 to 20 minutes
The temporary cessation or subsidence of a fever; the space of time between the paroxysms of a disease. Intermission is an entire cessation, as distinguished from remission, or abatement of fever

intermissive.definition: Having temporary cessations; not continual; intermittent

intermit.definition: To cause to cease for a time, or at intervals; to interrupt; to suspend
To cease for a time or at intervals; to moderate; to be intermittent, as a fever

intermittence.definition: Act or state of intermitting; intermission

intermittent.definition: Coming and going at intervals; alternating; recurrent; periodic; as, an intermittent fever

intermittently.definition: With intermissions; in an intermittent manner; intermittingly

intermix.definition: To be mixed together; to be intermingled

intermixture.definition: A mass formed by mixture; a mass of ingredients mixed

intermobility.definition: Capacity of things to move among each other; as, the intermobility of fluid particles

intermural.definition: Lying between walls; inclosed by walls
Taking place between two different institutions or cities; as, an intermural soccer match between two schools

intern.definition: To put for safe keeping in the interior of a place or country; to confine to one locality; as, to intern troops which have fled for refuge to a neutral country
To hold until the end of a war, as enemy citizens in a country at the time of outbreak of hostilities; -- an action performed by countries

A resident physician in a hospital, especially one who has recently received the Doctorate and is practising under supervision of experienced physicians, as a continuation of the training process; a house physician; also called houseman in Britain
A person working as an apprentice to gain experience in an occupation; sometimes the position is paid a salary, and other times it is not; as, a white house intern; an intern in a law firm

internal.definition: Inward; interior; being within any limit or surface; inclosed; -- opposed to external; as, the internal parts of a body, or of the earth
Derived from, or dependent on, the thing itself; inherent; as, the internal evidence of the divine origin of the Scriptures
Pertaining to its own affairs or interests; especially, (said of a country) domestic, as opposed to foreign; as, internal trade; internal troubles or war
Pertaining to the inner being or the heart; spiritual
Lying toward the mesial plane; mesial

internal-combustion.definition: Designating, or pertaining to, any engine (called an Internal-combustion engine) in which the heat or pressure energy necessary to produce motion is developed in the engine cylinder, as by the explosion of a gas, and not in a separate chamber, as in a steam-engine boiler. The gas used may be a fixed gas, or one derived from alcohol, ether, gasoline (petrol), naphtha, oil (petroleum), etc. There are three main classes: (1) gas engines proper, using fixed gases, as coal, blast-furnace, or producer gas; (2) engines using the vapor of a volatile fluid, as the typical gasoline (petrol) engine; (3) oil engines, using either an atomized spray or the vapor (produced by heat) of a comparatively heavy oil, as petroleum or kerosene. In all of these the gas is mixed with a definite amount of air, the charge is composed in the cylinder and is then exploded either by a flame of gas (flame ignition -- now little used), by a hot tube (tube ignition) or the like, by an electric spark (electric ignition, the usual method is gasoline engines, or by the heat of compression, as in the Diesel engine. Gas and oil engines are chiefly of the stationary type. Gasoline engines are largely used for automobile vehicles, boats, etc. Most internal-combustion engines use the Otto (four-stroke) cycle, though many use the two-stroke cycle. They are almost universally trunk engines and single-acting. Because of the intense heat produced by the frequent explosions, the cylinders must be cooled by a water jacket (water-cooled) or by air currents (air cooled) to give the maximum thermodynamic efficiency and to avoid excessive friction or seizing

internality.definition: The state of being internal or within; interiority

internalization.definition: learning (of values or attitudes etc.) that is incorporated within yourself

internally.definition: Inwardly; within the enveloping surface, or the boundary of a thing; within the body; beneath the surface

internasal.definition: Between the nasal cavities; as, the internasal cartilage

international.definition: Between or among nations; pertaining to the intercourse of nations; participated in by two or more nations; common to, or affecting, two or more nations
Of or concerning the association called the International
Independent of national boundaries; common to all people; as, the atmosphere is an international resource; the international community of scholars

The International; an abbreviated from of the title of the International Workingmen's Association, the name of an association, formed in London in 1864, which has for object the promotion of the interests of the industrial classes of all nations
A member of the International Association

internationalisation.definition: the act of bringing something under international control

internationalism.definition: The state or principles of international interests and intercourse
The doctrines or organization of the International

internationalist.definition: One who is versed in the principles of international law
A member of the International; one who believes in, or advocates the doctrines of, the International

internationalistic.definition: favoring cooperation among nations; -- of people and policies

internationality.definition: quality of being international in scope; as, he applauded the internationality of scientific terminology

internationalization.definition: the act of bringing something under international control

internationalize.definition: To make international; to cause to affect the mutual relations of two or more nations; as, to internationalize a principle of law, or a philanthropic enterprise

internationally.definition: In an international manner; from an international point of view

interne.definition: That which is within; the interior

internecine.definition: Involving, or accompanied by, mutual slaughter; mutually destructive
Of or pertaining to internal conflicts within a group; as, internecine quarrels

internet.definition: A large network{3} of numerous computers connected through a number of major nodes of high-speed computers having high-speed communications channels between the major nodes, and numerous minor nodes allowing electronic communication among millions of computers around the world; -- usually referred to as the internet.  It is the basis for the World-Wide Web

interneural.definition: Between the neural arches or neural spines

internment.definition: Confinement within narrow limits, -- as of foreign troops, to the interior of a country
Confining within a country for the duration of a war; -- usually of citizens of a hostile power

internodal.definition: Of or pertaining to internodes; intervening between nodes or joints

internode.definition: The space between two nodes or points of the stem from which the leaves properly arise
A part between two joints; a segment; specifically, one of the phalanges

internship.definition: The state of being an intern; the position of an intern
The period of time during which a person is an intern; as, she served her internship over the summer
A program to provide novices in a field with apprenticeship training
The period of time during which a novice in a field serves in a subordinate capacity and continues to gain experience; the learning period before one becomes an expert

internuncial.definition: Of or pertaining to an internuncio
Communicating or transmitting impressions between different parts of the body; -- said of the nervous system

internuncio.definition: A representative, or chargé d'affaires, of the pope at a foreign court or seat of government, ranking next below a nuncio

internuncioship.definition: The office or function of an internuncio

interoceanic.definition: Between oceans; connecting oceans; as, interoceanic communication; an interoceanic canal

interocular.definition: Between, or within, the eyes; as, the interocular distance; situated between the eyes, as the antennæ of some insects

interoperability.definition: The quality of being interoperable.  Used of data structures or executable programs

interoperable.definition: Being able to function in two or more different programs or operating systems.  Used of data structures or executable programs; as, Microsoft Word files are interoperable between Intel and Macintosh operating environments

interopercular.definition: Of or pertaining to the interoperculum

interoperculum.definition: The postero-inferior opercular bone, in fishes

interorbital.definition: Between the orbits; as, the interorbital septum

interosculant.definition: Mutually touching or intersecting; as, interosculant circles
Uniting two groups; -- said of certain genera which connect family groups, or of species that connect genera. See Osculant

interosculate.definition: To kiss together to touch. See Osculate
To have the character of, or to lie between, two distinct groups

interosseal.definition: Situated between bones; as, an interosseous ligament

interpale.definition: To place pales between or among; to separate by pales

interparietal.definition: Between the parietal bones or cartilages; as, the interparietal suture

interpedencular.definition: Between peduncles; esp., between the peduncles, or crura, of the cerebrum

interpel.definition: To interrupt, break in upon, or intercede with

interpellate.definition: To question imperatively, as a minister, or other executive officer, in explanation of his conduct; -- generally on the part of a legislative body

interpellation.definition: The act of interpelling or interrupting; interruption
The act of interposing or interceding; intercession
An act of interpellating, or of demanding of an officer an explanation of his action; imperative or peremptory questioning; a point raised in a debate

interpenetrate.definition: To penetrate between or within; to penetrate mutually
To penetrate each the other; to penetrate between bodies or their parts

interpenetration.definition: The act or process of penetrating between or within other substances; mutual penetration; also, the result of a process of interpenetration

interpenetrative.definition: Penetrating among or between other substances; penetrating each the other; mutually penetrative

interpetalary.definition: Between the petals of a flower

interpilaster.definition: The interval or space between two pilasters

interplace.definition: To place between or among; as, to interplace a name

interplanetary.definition: Between planets; as, interplanetary spaces; interplanetary travel

interplay.definition: Mutual action or influence; interaction; as, the interplay of affection

interplead.definition: To plead against each other, or go to trial between themselves, as the claimants in an in an interpleader. See Interpleader

interpleader.definition: A proceeding devised to enable a person, of whom the same debt, duty, or thing is claimed adversely by two or more parties, to compel them to litigate the right or title between themselves, and thereby to relieve himself from the suits which they might otherwise bring against him

interpoint.definition: To point; to mark with stops or pauses; to punctuate

interpolable.definition: That may be interpolated; suitable to be interpolated

interpolate.definition: To renew; to carry on with intermission
To alter or corrupt by the insertion of new or foreign matter; especially, to change, as a book or text, by the insertion of matter that is new, or foreign to the purpose of the author

To fill up intermediate terms of, as of a series, according to the law of the series; to introduce, as a number or quantity, in a partial series, according to the law of that part of the series; to estimate a value at a point intermediate between points of knwon value.  Compare extrapolate

interpolated.definition: Inserted in, or added to, the original; introduced; foisted in; changed by the insertion of new or spurious matter
Provided with necessary interpolations; as, an interpolated table

interpolation.definition: The act of introducing or inserting anything, especially that which is spurious or foreign
That which is introduced or inserted, especially something foreign or spurious
The method or operation of finding from a few given terms of a series, as of numbers or observations, other intermediate terms in conformity with the law of the series

interpolator.definition: One who interpolates; esp., one who inserts foreign or spurious matter in genuine writings

interpone.definition: To interpose; to insert or place between

interponent.definition: One who, or that which, interposes; an interloper, an opponent

interposal.definition: The act of interposing; interposition; intervention

interpose.definition: To place between; as, to interpose a screen between the eye and the light
To thrust; to intrude; to put between, either for aid or for troubling
To introduce or inject between the parts of a conversation or argument
To step in between parties at variance; to mediate; as, the prince interposed and made peace
To utter a sentiment by way of interruption

interposer.definition: One who, or that which, interposes or intervenes; an obstacle or interruption; a mediator or agent between parties

interposit.definition: An intermediate depot or station between one commercial city or country and another

interposition.definition: The act of interposing, or the state of being interposed; a being, placing, or coming between; mediation

interpret.definition: To explain or tell the meaning of; to expound; to translate orally into intelligible or familiar language or terms; to decipher; to define; -- applied esp. to language, but also to dreams, signs, conduct, mysteries, etc.; as, to interpret the Hebrew language to an Englishman; to interpret an Indian speech
To apprehend and represent by means of art; to show by illustrative representation; as, an actor interprets the character of Hamlet; a musician interprets a sonata; an artist interprets a landscape

interpretable.definition: Admitting of interpretation; capable of being interpreted or explained

interpretation.definition: The act of interpreting; explanation of what is obscure; translation; version; construction; as, the interpretation of a foreign language, of a dream, or of an enigma
The sense given by an interpreter; exposition or explanation given; meaning; as, commentators give various interpretations of the same passage of Scripture
An artist's way of expressing his thought or embodying his conception of nature
The act or process of applying general principles or formulæ to the explanation of the results obtained in special cases

interpretative.definition: Designed or fitted to interpret; explanatory

interpreter.definition: One who or that which interprets, explains, or expounds; a translator; especially, a person who translates orally between two parties

interpubic.definition: Between the pubic bones or cartilages; as, the interpubic disk

interpunction.definition: The insertion of points between words or sentences; punctuation

interradial.definition: Between the radii, or rays; -- in Zoology, said of certain parts of radiate animals; as, the interradial plates of a starfish

interramal.definition: Between rami or branches; esp., between the mandibles, or rami of the lower jaw; intermandibular

interregent.definition: A person who discharges the royal functions during an interregnum

interregnum.definition: The time during which a throne is vacant between the death or abdication of a sovereign and the accession of his successor
Any period during which, for any cause, the executive branch of a government is suspended or interrupted

interrelated.definition: Having a mutual or reciprocal relation or parallelism; correlative

interrelatedness.definition: mutual or reciprocal relation or relatedness; interrelation

interrenal.definition: Between the kidneys; as, the interrenal body, an organ found in many fishes

interrogate.definition: To question formally; to question; to examine by asking questions; as, to interrogate a witness

interrogation.definition: The act or process of interrogating or questioning; examination by questions; an instance of interrogating; inquiry

A point, mark, or sign, thus [?], indicating that the sentence with which it is connected is a question. It is used to express doubt, or to mark a query.  Usually called a question mark; called also interrogation point

interrogative.definition: Denoting a question; expressed in the form of a question; as, an interrogative sentence; an interrogative pronoun
A word used in asking questions; as, who? which? why?

interrogatively.definition: In the form of, or by means of, a question; in an interrogative manner

interrogator.definition: One who asks questions; a questioner

interrogatory.definition: Containing, expressing, or implying a question; as, an interrogatory sentence

interrupt.definition: To break into, or between; to stop, or hinder by breaking in upon the course or progress of; to interfere with the current or motion of; to cause a temporary cessation of; as, to interrupt the remarks of anyone speaking
To divide; to separate; to break the monotony of; as, the evenness of the road was not interrupted by a single hill

interrupted.definition: Irregular; -- said of any arrangement whose symmetry is destroyed by local causes, as when leaflets are interposed among the leaves in a pinnate leaf

interrupter.definition: One who, or that which, interrupts
A device for opening and closing an electrical circuit; a vibrating spring or tuning fork, arranged to make and break a circuit at rapidly recurring intervals, by the action of the current itself

interruption.definition: The act of interrupting, or breaking in upon
The state of being interrupted; a breach or break, caused by the abrupt intervention of something foreign; intervention; interposition

Obstruction caused by breaking in upon course, current, progress, or motion; stop; hindrance; as, the author has met with many interruptions in the execution of his work; the speaker or the argument proceeds without interruption

interscapular.definition: Between the scapulæ or shoulder blades
Pertaining to the upper back, or the part between the shoulders; as, the interscapular feathers

interscapulars.definition: The interscapular feathers of a bird

interscendent.definition: Having exponents which are radical quantities; -- said of certain powers; as, x√2, or x√a

intersect.definition: To cut into or between; to cut or cross mutually; to divide into parts; as, any two diameters of a circle intersect each other at the center
To cut into one another; to meet and cross each other; as, the point where two lines intersect

intersectant.definition: having at least one spatial point in common

intersection.definition: The act, state, or place of intersecting
The point or line in which one line or surface cuts another

intersectional.definition: Pertaining to, or formed by, intersections

interseptal.definition: Between septa; as, the interseptal spaces or zones, between the transparent, or septal, zones in striated muscle; the interseptal chambers of a shell, or of a seed vessel

intersert.definition: To put in between other things; to insert

interserttion.definition: The act of interserting, or that which is interserted

intersesamoid.definition: Between sesamoid bones; as, intersesamoid ligaments

intersidereal.definition: Between or among constellations or stars; interstellar

intersocial.definition: Pertaining to the mutual intercourse or relations of persons in society; social

intersomnious.definition: Between the times of sleeping; in an interval of wakefulness

intersperse.definition: To scatter or set here and there among other things; to insert at intervals; as, to intersperse pictures in a book
To diversify or adorn with things set or scattered at intervals; to place something at intervals in or among; as, to intersperse a book with pictures

interspersion.definition: The act of interspersing, or the state of being interspersed

interspinal.definition: Between spines; esp., between the spinous processes of the vertebral column

interspiration.definition: Spiritual inspiration at separate times, or at intervals

interstapedial.definition: Pertaining to a part of the columella of the ear, between the stapes and the mediostapedial

interstate.definition: Pertaining to the mutual relations of States; existing between, or including, different States; as, interstate commerce
An interstate highway, part of the United States Interstate Highway system

interstate commerce.definition: Commerce that involves transportation of articles of commerce across state lines

interstate commerce commission.definition: The governmental commision charged with making and enforcing regulations concerning interstate commerce

interstellar.definition: Between or among the stars; as, interstellar space

intersternal.definition: Between the sternal; -- said of certain membranes or parts of insects and crustaceans

interstice.definition: That which intervenes between one thing and another; especially, a space between things closely set, or between the parts which compose a body; a narrow chink; a crack; a crevice; a hole; an interval; as, the interstices of a wall
An interval of time; specifically (R. C. Ch.), in the plural, the intervals which the canon law requires between the reception of the various degrees of orders

intersticed.definition: Provided with interstices; having interstices between; situated at intervals

interstitial.definition: Of or pertaining to interstices; intermediate; within the tissues; as, interstitial cavities or spaces in the tissues of animals or plants

interstition.definition: An intervening period of time; interval

interstratification.definition: Stratification among or between other layers or strata; also, that which is interstratified

interstratified.definition: Stratified among or between other bodies; as, interstratified rocks

interstratify.definition: To put or insert between other strata

intertarsal.definition: Between the tarsal bones; as, the intertarsal articulations

intertex.definition: To intertwine; to weave or bind together

intertexture.definition: The act of interweaving, or the state of being interwoven; that which is interwoven

intertie.definition: In any framed work, a horizontal tie other than sill and plate or other principal ties, securing uprights to one another

intertransverse.definition: Between the transverse processes of the vertebræ

intertrigo.definition: A rubbing or chafing of the skin; especially, an abrasion or excoriation of the skin between folds, as in fat or neglected children

intertrochanteric.definition: Between the trochanters of the femur

intertropical.definition: Situated between or within the tropics

intertubular.definition: Between tubes or tubules; as, intertubular cells; intertubular substance

intertwine.definition: To unite by twining one with another; to entangle; to interlace
To be twined or twisted together; to become mutually involved or enfolded
The act of intertwining, or the state of being intertwined

intertwist.definition: To twist together one with another; to intertwine

interurban.definition: Going between, or connecting, cities or towns; as, interurban electric railways

interval.definition: A space between things; a void space intervening between any two objects; as, an interval between two houses or hills
Space of time between any two points or events; as, the interval between the death of Charles I. of England, and the accession of Charles II
A brief space of time between the recurrence of similar conditions or states; as, the interval between paroxysms of pain; intervals of sanity or delirium
Difference in pitch between any two tones

A tract of low ground between hills, or along the banks of a stream, usually alluvial land, enriched by the overflowings of the river, or by fertilizing deposits of earth from the adjacent hills.  Cf. Bottom, n., 7

intervary.definition: To alter or vary between; to change

intervene.definition: To come between, or to be between, persons or things; -- followed by between; as, the Mediterranean intervenes between Europe and Africa

To occur, fall, or come between, points of time, or events; as, an instant intervened between the flash and the report; nothing intervened ( i. e., between the intention and the execution) to prevent the undertaking
To interpose; as, to intervene to settle a quarrel
In a suit to which one has not been made a party, to put forward a defense of one's interest in the   subject matter

intervener.definition: One who intervenes; especially (Law), a person who assumes a part in a suit between others

intervenient.definition: Being or coming between; intercedent; interposed

intervention.definition: Any interference that may affect the interests of others; especially, of one or more states with the affairs of another; -- the intervention of one state in the affairs of another is typically unwelcome by the state being intervened in, but some cases of mediation between states may be called intervention.  Opposed to nonintervention
The act by which a third person, to protect his own interest, interposes and becomes a party to a suit pending between other parties

interventor.definition: One who intervenes; a mediator; especially (Eccles. Hist.), a person designated by a church to reconcile parties, and unite them in the choice of officers

interventricular.definition: Between the ventricles; as, the interventricular partition of the heart

intervert.definition: To turn to another course or use

interview.definition: A mutual sight or view; a meeting face to face; usually, a formal or official meeting for consultation; a conference; as, the secretary had an interview with the President
A conversation, or questioning, for the purpose of eliciting information for publication; the published statement so elicited
To have an interview with; to question or converse with, especially for the purpose of obtaining information for publication

interviewer.definition: One who interviews; especially, one who obtains an interview with another for the purpose of eliciting his opinions or obtaining information for publication

interviewing.definition: The act or custom of holding an interview or interviews

intervisible.definition: Mutually visible, or in sight, the one from the other, as stations

intervocalic.definition: Situated between vowels; immediately preceded and followed by vowel sounds, as, p in occupy, d in idea, etc

intervolution.definition: The state of being intervolved or coiled up; a convolution; as, the intervolutions of a snake

intervolve.definition: To involve one within another; to twist or coil together

interweave.definition: To weave together; to intermix or unite in texture or construction; to intertwine; as, threads of silk and cotton interwoven
To intermingle; to unite intimately; to connect closely; as, to interweave truth with falsehood

interwish.definition: To wish mutually in regarded to each other

interworking.definition: The act of working in together; interweaving

interwreathe.definition: To weave into a wreath; to intertwine
